"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, Scotty here, and today I want to talk about cover crops and soil aggregates. This is my vegetable garden, and we just recently but it's between seasons, so we put down a cover crop, which is uh a non-productive crop that's just there for soil health. And this is a crop of crimson clover, winter rye, and legumes. And uh almost immediately, even really before it's had a chance to really come up uh more than this, you can see the soil is looking bound together in a much more comprehensive way than that bed over there that does not have the cover crop, and I'll give you a little close-up that a second. But if you look, there there's almost like a ceiling of the the soil. And here's a real good example here. This is a soil aggregate. You see how it's all kind of bound together? You can just squeeze and it all pops apart because the only thing making that glue happen is the residue of gar uh organic matter. And this is going to help with the soil mechanics, and that means more water retention, better carbon retention, everything else, and you can just see how loose all that is. Anyway, thanks.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, Scotty here, and today I want to talk about cover crops and soil aggregates.\",\n      \"start\": 0.24,\n      \"end\": 5.12,\n      \"duration\": 4.88,\n      \"confidence\": 0.991,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.4,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.989\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.72,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.72,\n          \"end